Question 1

Recall the data sexSells.csv from the previous homework. Calculate the correlation between the recall of ads with a sexual image and ads without the sexual image. Consider the direction of the correlation, what does this comunicate about this data?

  • Use of cor() and cor.test() is not permitted.
library(tidyverse)

# Load data and put in order
ads <- read_csv("data/sexSells.csv") |> 
  arrange(Image, Subject)
# Converting to wide format
ads_wide <- ads |> 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Image, values_from = AdRecall)

# Calculate z-scores
ads_wide$sexy_z <- (ads_wide$Sexy - mean(ads_wide$Sexy)) / sd(ads_wide$Sexy)

ads_wide$not_sexy_z <- 
  (ads_wide$NotSexy - mean(ads_wide$NotSexy)) / sd(ads_wide$NotSexy)

# Correlation
N <- nrow(ads_wide)

R <- sum(ads_wide$sexy_z * ads_wide$not_sexy_z) / (N - 1)
R
[1] 0.524884

There is a positive correlation indicating that people who are more likely to recall the sexy ads are also more likely to recall the non-sexy ads.


Question 2

Plot a scatterplot looking at the relationship between the recall of the two types of ads. Place nonsexual ads on the x-axis and sexual ads on the y-axis. You will probably notice that there is something odd about how the plot looks, what do think is causing the oddness?

ggplot(ads_wide, aes(x = NotSexy, y = Sexy)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

There are 39 x-y pairs, but only 24 points plotted. This is because there is âoverplottingâ on the graph (i.e., some x-y pairs are identical and thus the points are overlapping each other).

Tip

Since the data has some overplotting in it, a good idea is to use geom_jitter() instead of geom_point(). This will add a bit of random variation to the location of each point. I never showed you this in class, but now you know.


Question 3

Construct a linear model that predicts the number of sexual ads recalled given the number of non-sexual ads recalled.

  • Use of lm() is not permitted.
  • Report the formula you produced. E.g., \(\hat{y} = \text{(intercept value)} + \text{(slope value)} \cdot x\)
  • Plot it on your scatterplot.
# Slope
b1 <- R * (sd(ads_wide$Sexy) / sd(ads_wide$NotSexy))

# Intercept
b0 <- mean(ads_wide$Sexy) - b1 * mean(ads_wide$NotSexy)

Formula:

\(\hat{y} = 1.799 + 0.557 \cdot x\)

# Plot
ggplot(ads_wide, aes(x = NotSexy, y = Sexy)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3) +
  geom_abline(
    intercept = b0, 
    slope = b1,
    colour = "darkorange1",
    linewidth = 2
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Non-Sexy Ads",
    y = "Sexy Ads"
  ) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))
Note

Use of geom_jitter() instead of geom_point() is not necessary here for marks.


Question 4

You own an ice cream business and you would like to create a linear model that could predict the daily revenue in dollars based on the outside air temperature (degrees celsius). Use the data IceCreamData.csv to create this model.

  • Use of lm(), cor, and cor.test() is not permitted.
  • Report the modelâs formula.
ice_cream <- read_csv("data/IceCreamData.csv")

# Sample size
N <- nrow(ice_cream)
# Correlation
temp_z <- (ice_cream$Temperature - mean(ice_cream$Temperature)) /
  sd(ice_cream$Temperature)
rev_z <- (ice_cream$Revenue - mean(ice_cream$Revenue)) /
  sd(ice_cream$Revenue)

R <- sum(temp_z * rev_z) / (N - 1)
# Slope
b1 <- R * (sd(ice_cream$Revenue) / sd(ice_cream$Temperature))

# Intercept
b0 <- mean(ice_cream$Revenue) - b1 * mean(ice_cream$Temperature)

Formula:

\(\hat{y} = 44.831 + 21.444 \cdot x\)

Question 6

Create a plot of the residuals for the ice cream model you created. Does the plot indicate any patterns or heteroscedasticity?

  • Use of lm() is not permitted.
# Model predictions (y_hat)
ice_cream$y_hat <- b0 + b1 * ice_cream$Temperature

# Residuals
ice_cream$resid <- ice_cream$Revenue - ice_cream$y_hat
ggplot(ice_cream, aes(x = Temperature, y = resid)) +
  geom_point(
    shape = 21, size = 3,
    fill = "#F7DBEC", 
    colour = "#A57E56", 
    stroke = .5
  ) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = 3) +
  ylab("Residuals") +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

There are no obvious patterns or heteroscedasticity.


Question 7

Assess the normality of the residuals from the previous question - is it reasonable to assume they are normally distributed?

  • Use of lm() is not permitted.
ggplot(ice_cream, aes(sample = resid)) +

It seems reasonable to assume the residuals are normally distributed.

Question 9

Report the standard error of the intercept and slope for the previous questionâs model.

  • Use of lm() is not permitted.
#Squared Standard Error of the Residuals
N <- nrow(ice_cream)
res_var <- sum((ice_cream$Revenue - ice_cream$y_hat)^2)/ (N - 2)

#Sum of Squares for X
ss_x <- sum((ice_cream$Temperature - mean(ice_cream$Temperature))^2)

#Slope Standard Error
s_b1 <- sqrt(res_var / ss_x)

#Intercept Standard Error
s_b0 <- sqrt((res_var * sum(ice_cream$Temperature^2)) / (N * ss_x))

# Results
paste0("Intercept Std. Error: ", round(s_b0, 5))
paste0("Slope Std. Error: ", round(s_b1, 5))
[1] "Intercept Std. Error: 3.27176"
[1] "Slope Std. Error: 0.13829"


Question 10

Conduct a t-test on the slope from the ice cream model. Use of lm() and confint() is not permitted. Report the following:

  • null hypothesis
  • test statistic
  • degrees of freedom
  • p-value
  • confidence interval
# Test Statistic
beta1 <- 0
t_stat <- (b1 - beta1) / s_b1

# Degrees of Freedom
P <- 1
df <- N - P - 1

# P-value
p <- pt(t_stat, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# T_crit
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

# Confidence Interval
lower <- b1 - t_crit * s_b1
upper <- b1 + t_crit * s_b1

# Results
paste0("H0: B1 = 0")
paste0("T = ", round(t_stat, 4))
paste0("df = ", round(df, 4))
paste0("p = ", p)
paste0("95% CI: [", round(lower, 4), ", ", round(upper, 4), "]")
[1] "H0: B1 = 0"
[1] "T = 155.0572"
[1] "df = 498"
[1] "p = 0"
[1] "95% CI: [21.1719, 21.7153]"
